’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, but Bromley (near Bow) in Greater London is from Old English <i>bræmbel</i> ‘bramble’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Brimley","meanings":["habitational name, perhaps from Brimley in Devon or Brimbley in Stoke Abbott, Dorset, both named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","variant of   Bromley  .","English:"]},{"name":"Brumley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bromley  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Lady Thomas Bromley was born in 1303, in Bromley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Thomas Bromley in 1318, in Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1303–":"1303–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1303":"1303","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1370":"1370","1318":"1318","Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England","Bromley, London, England":"Bromley, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bromley, Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bromley, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1303–":"1303–Kuollut","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1303–Female":"1303–Kuollut","1303":"1303","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1370":"1370","1318":"1318","Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, En